Here is a Metal compute kernel to Gaussian blur an image:

```metal
#include <metal_stdlib>
#include <simd/simd.h>

using namespace metal;

kernel void gaussianBlur(texture2d<float, access::read> inTexture [[texture(0)]],
                         texture2d<float, access::write> outTexture [[texture(1)]],
                         uint2 gid [[thread_position_in_grid]]) 
{
    // Image size
    uint width = inTexture.get_width();
    uint height = inTexture.get_height();

    // Gaussian kernel size (must be odd)
    int kernelSize = 5;

    // Sigma value for Gaussian distribution
    float sigma = 2.0;

    // Calculate Gaussian kernel weights
    float weights[kernelSize];
    float sum = 0.0;
    for (int i = 0; i < kernelSize; i++) {
        float x = (float(i) - kernelSize / 2.0);
        weights[i] = exp(-x * x / (2.0 * sigma * sigma)) / (sigma * sqrt(2.0 * M_PI));
        sum += weights[i];
    }

    // Normalize weights to sum to 1.0
    for (int i = 0; i < kernelSize; i++) {
        weights[i] /= sum;
    }

    // Apply Gaussian blur
    float4 color = float4(0.0);
    for (int x = -kernelSize / 2; x <= kernelSize / 2; x++) {
        for (int y = -kernelSize / 2; y <= kernelSize / 2; y++) {
            int2 samplePos = gid + int2(x, y);
            if (all(samplePos >= 0 && samplePos < int2(width, height))) {
                float4 sampleColor = inTexture.read(samplePos);
                color += sampleColor * weights[x + kernelSize / 2] * weights[y + kernelSize / 2];
            }
        }
    }

    // Write blurred color to output
    outTexture.write(color, gid);
}
```

This kernel:

- Defines a 5x5 Gaussian kernel with sigma = 2.0
- Calculates the weights for the kernel
- Loops over the kernel size and samples the input texture
- Multiplies each sample by the kernel weight and accumulates
- Writes the blurred color to the output texture

This will perform a Gaussian blur on the input texture and write the result to the output texture.

Here is a Metal compute kernel to perform a Gaussian blur on a 2D image:

```swift
#include <metal_stdlib>
using namespace metal;

kernel void gaussianBlur(texture2d<float, access::read> inTexture [[texture(0)]],
                          texture2d<float, access::write> outTexture [[texture(1)]],
                          uint2 gid [[thread_position_in_grid]]) {

    const int kernelSize = 5;
    const float sigma = 2.0;
    const float weights[kernelSize] = {0.06136, 0.24477, 0.38774, 0.24477, 0.06136};

    float3 blurColor = float3(0.0);

    for (int i = -kernelSize/2; i <= kernelSize/2; i++) {
        for (int j = -kernelSize/2; j <= kernelSize/2; j++) {
            int2 samplePos = gid + int2(i, j);
            float weight = weights[i + kernelSize/2] * weights[j + kernelSize/2];
            blurColor += inTexture.read(samplePos).rgb * weight;
        }
    }

    outTexture.write(float4(blurColor, 1.0), gid);
}
```

This samples the input texture in a kernelSize x kernelSize region around each pixel, multiplying sampled pixel colors by a weighting from a 1D Gaussian kernel. It accumulates these weighted samples into blurColor, then writes the result to the output texture.

The sigma value adjusts the spread of the Gaussian kernel. Larger sigma gives more blurring. kernelSize should be adjusted to fit sigma, e.g. kernelSize = ceil(sigma * 3) + 1.

In UE5, to create an object later, for example in PreInitializeComponents, you can use the following steps:

1. Declare a variable of the object type you want to create in the header file of your class.
2. In the constructor of your class, initialize the variable to nullptr.
3. In PreInitializeComponents, create the object using the NewObject function and assign it to the variable.

Here is an example:

```
#include "UObject/ConstructorHelpers.h"
#include "UObject/UObjectGlobals.h"

UCLASS()
class UMyActor : public AActor
{
    GENERATED_BODY()

public:
    // Declare the variable
    UStaticMeshComponent* MyStaticMeshComponent;

    UMyActor();
    void PreInitializeComponents() override;
};

UMyActor::UMyActor()
{
    // Initialize the variable to nullptr
    MyStaticMeshComponent = nullptr;
}

void UMyActor::PreInitializeComponents()
{
    Super::PreInitializeComponents();

    // Create the object using the NewObject function and assign it to the variable
    MyStaticMeshComponent = NewObject<UStaticMeshComponent>(this, UStaticMeshComponent::StaticClass());
}
```

This will create a UStaticMeshComponent object and assign it to the MyStaticMeshComponent variable in the PreInitializeComponents function.

In Unreal Engine 5 (UE5), `CreateDefaultSubobject` is indeed used within the constructor of a class derived from `UObject` to create components or other UObject-derived subobjects that are intended to exist for the entire lifetime of the parent object. These subobjects are also automatically replicated, serialized, and integrated into the Unreal Engine's garbage collection system.

However, if you need to create an object at a later time, such as during the `PreInitializeComponents` phase or at any point after the constructor has run, you should not use `CreateDefaultSubobject`. Instead, you can use the `NewObject` function to dynamically create instances of UObjects.

Here's an example of how you might create a component during the `PreInitializeComponents` override:

```cpp
void AMyActor::PreInitializeComponents()
{
    Super::PreInitializeComponents();

    // Make sure to only do this once and that the component is not already created
    if (MyDynamicComponent == nullptr)
    {
        MyDynamicComponent = NewObject<UMyComponent>(this, UMyComponent::StaticClass());

        if (MyDynamicComponent != nullptr)
        {
            // Optionally set any properties on the component
            MyDynamicComponent->SetSomeProperty(SomeValue);

            // Register the component with the engine so it gets updated/rendered
            MyDynamicComponent->RegisterComponent();

            // If you want to attach it to an existing component, do so here
            MyDynamicComponent->AttachToComponent(GetRootComponent(), FAttachmentTransformRules::KeepRelativeTransform);
        }
    }
}
```

In the above example, `MyDynamicComponent` is a UPROPERTY member of `AMyActor`. It's a pointer that's initially null and gets assigned a newly created instance of `UMyComponent` by using `NewObject`. After creating the new component, it's registered with the engine using `RegisterComponent`, so that it becomes part of the actor's component hierarchy and receives updates. If you want to attach the new component to another component, such as the root component, you would use `AttachToComponent`.

Please note that when you dynamically create components like this, they are not automatically replicated or saved/loaded with the actor unless you set those properties manually. In contrast, components created with `CreateDefaultSubobject` in the constructor are automatically set up for replication and serialization.

Always remember to check if the object has already been created before creating a new one to avoid memory leaks and unnecessary object creation.

