In Flutter, if you want to print messages to the console from the Windows native code layer, you cannot use `printf` directly because it will not show up in the Flutter debug console. Instead, you should use the Windows-specific logging functions.

Here's an example of how you can use `OutputDebugString` to log messages that will appear in debug tools like Visual Studio's Output window or the Debug Console in Visual Studio Code when running a Flutter app on Windows:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>

// ...

void LogMessage(const std::wstring& message) {
    OutputDebugString(message.c_str());
    OutputDebugString(L"\n");
}

// ...

// Use it like this in your code
LogMessage(L"This will be logged to the debug console");
```

To use this in your C++ code, make sure you include the `<windows.h>` header. Note that `OutputDebugString` takes a wide string (`LPCWSTR`) as its parameter. If you have a narrow string (`std::string`), you need to convert it to a wide string (`std::wstring`) before passing it to `OutputDebugString`.

If you want to log messages from C code, you can do the following:

```c
#include <windows.h>

// ...

void LogMessage(const wchar_t* message) {
    OutputDebugString(message);
    OutputDebugString(L"\n");
}

// ...

// Use it like this in your code
LogMessage(L"This will be logged to the debug console");
```

Again, ensure you are passing a wide string (`L"This is a message"`), as `OutputDebugString` requires it.

