In TypeScript, there are two main ways to define object types:

1. Interfaces:

```ts
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}
```

2. Type aliases: 

```ts
type User = {
  name: string;
  age: number; 
}
```

The main differences between interfaces and type aliases are:

1. Interfaces can be extended and implemented by classes, type aliases can't.

2. Interfaces create a new name that is used everywhere. Type aliases simply create a new name for an existing type.

3. Interfaces can be merged, type aliases can't.

Some examples:

Extending interfaces:
```ts
interface User {
  name: string;
}

interface User extends Profile {
  age: number; 
}
```

Implementing interfaces:
```ts
class User implements Profile {
  name: string;
  age: number;
} 
```

Merging interfaces:
```ts
interface Window {
  title: string; 
}

interface Window {
  tsconfig: TsConfig; 
}

// Equivalent to
interface Window {
  title: string;
  tsconfig: TsConfig; 
}
```

So in summary:

- Use interfaces when you may need to extend or implement them in the future.
- Use type aliases when you just want to alias an existing type to a new name.

